**Content Approach:** Most competitors treat vampy nails as either a Halloween sub-topic or a colour guide. They list shades and shapes but do not explore the aesthetic identity of vampy nails — what it signals, why it resonates, or how it lives differently across vibes (dark romance vs classic goth vs corporate-appropriate). Almost none address the mood-matching dimension: what design fits what occasion, what energy, what personal aesthetic.

**Visual Patterns:** Inspirational nail content in this space typically runs 10–15 images. Higher-performing pins use one strong hero image plus tightly curated design galleries per section.

**Recommended Image Count:** 12–15 images — each H2 design section needs one or two visual anchors.

### Competitor Gaps (Our Opportunity)
**Unanswered Questions:**
- What actually counts as "vampy" — where does the line sit between vampy and just red?
- How do I make vampy nails feel intentional rather than costume-y outside October?
- Which vampy design works best for my specific vibe (dark romance vs goth edge vs boardroom adjacent)?
- Can I do a vampy look on short nails without it looking unfinished?
- What's the 2026 evolution of vampy — is the classic red-black combo still the move?
- What finish (matte vs gloss vs velvet) changes the mood of the same vampy colour?

**Missing Semantic Territory:**
- The cultural history of vampy nails (Chanel Vamp/Rouge Noir origin story) — almost no competitor tells this
- Vampy as a year-round aesthetic identity vs a seasonal trend — underexplored
- Skin tone guidance for vampy shades — almost entirely absent in competitor content
- The dark romance sub-niche within vampy (red ombre, lace details, blood moon) vs classic goth edge

**Audience Blind Spots:**
- Readers want to see themselves in the designs — competitors don't map designs to personality or occasion
- No one covers the "professional vampy" angle (short almond in deep wine as a genuinely chic work nail)
- The "how does this translate to short nails" question is answered poorly or only as an afterthought

### Our Strategic Approach
**Differentiation:** Go beyond a colour and shape list — frame vampy nails as an aesthetic with a spectrum. Map different vampy expressions (blood red classic, dark romance, wearable oxblood, gothic edge) to the reader's vibe, occasion, and nail length so they leave knowing exactly which look is theirs.

**Structure Plan:** Organise around mood and wearability rather than just colour. Let the visual gallery do the inspiration work; let the copy do the identity work — this is who this nail is for, this is when to wear it, this is why it works.

**Tone Direction:** Dark glamour confidence — warm but knowing. Speak like the friend who has genuinely lived in this aesthetic, not a beauty editor describing it from outside.

